stylometry: Sensitivity analysis allows you to look at different independent variables, and how these independent variables effect the dependent variable. It is important because it allows you to see if profits (or your target cell) changes when independent variables are changed. For example, in a fixed cost problem selling shirts, shorts, skirts, and jackets, profits may be high when selling only shorts and jackets, but if you use the sensitivity analysis and change the amount of skirts sold, this may show an increase in profits. SolverTable allows you to change different independent variables and set different response rates. For example, a 5% response rate might be set, which means the algorithm is 5% away from the optimal solution (and sometimes, this may even be a high response rate) SolverTable goes through all possible solutions.
